## Summary

Tool execution approval (`needsApproval: true`) works correctly in the Core API (`generateText`/`streamText`) but is broken in the UI API (`ToolLoopAgent` + `createAgentUIStream`) when using the Anthropic provider.

## SDK version

- `ai`: `6.0.69`
- `@ai-sdk/anthropic`: `3.0.36`

## Expected behaviour

When a user approves a tool via `addToolApprovalResponse()` and the client sends a new request with `approval-responded` UIMessage state, the SDK should intercept the approval, execute the tool, and send Anthropic a valid `tool_result` block â€” identical to how the Core API handles it.

## Actual behaviour

The Anthropic provider explicitly skips `tool-approval-response` content types:

```typescript
// @ai-sdk/anthropic provider, content conversion loop
if (content.type === "tool-approval-response") {
  continue; // skipped â€” no tool execution, no tool_result produced
}
```

Anthropic receives a `tool_use` block with no corresponding `tool_result` and throws:

```
"tool_use ids were found without tool_result blocks immediately after: toolu_xxx"
```

## Why Core API works but UI API doesn't

In the **Core API**, when `generateText` receives a `tool-approval-response` message, it intercepts it before reaching the provider, executes the tool, and replaces it with a `tool_result`. Anthropic only ever sees completed tool calls.

In the **UI API**, `createAgentUIStream` calls `convertToModelMessages` which produces a `tool-approval-response` message and passes it directly to the Anthropic provider â€” which drops it. The interception step that exists in the Core API path is missing in the UI API + Anthropic provider path.

## Repro

```typescript
const tool = tool({
  description: 'Create an issue',
  inputSchema: z.object({ title: z.string() }),
  needsApproval: true,
  execute: async ({ title }) => ({ id: '123', title }),
});

const agent = new ToolLoopAgent({ model: anthropic('claude-sonnet-4-5'), tools: { createIssue: tool } });

// Stream 1: agent pauses with approval-requested
const stream1 = await createAgentUIStream({ agent, uiMessages });

// User approves â€” client sends new request with approval-responded state
// Stream 2: Anthropic throws
const stream2 = await createAgentUIStream({ agent, uiMessages: messagesWithApprovalResponded });
// Error: "tool_use ids were found without tool_result blocks immediately after"
```

## Workaround

We manually intercept `approval-responded` parts before calling `createAgentUIStream`, execute the tool directly, and transition the state to `output-available`. This replicates what the Core API does natively:

```typescript
async function resolveApprovalResponses(uiMessages, tools) {
  const lastMessage = uiMessages[uiMessages.length - 1];
  if (!lastMessage?.parts) return uiMessages;

  const resolvedMessage = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(lastMessage));

  for (const part of resolvedMessage.parts) {
    if (part.state !== 'approval-responded') continue;

    const toolName = part.toolName ?? part.type?.slice(5);

    if (!part.approval?.approved) {
      part.state = 'output-denied';
      continue;
    }

    const tool = tools[toolName];
    if (tool?.execute) {
      const output = await tool.execute(part.input, { toolCallId: part.toolCallId, messages: [], abortSignal: new AbortController().signal });
      part.state = 'output-available';
      part.output = output;
    }
  }

  return [...uiMessages.slice(0, -1), resolvedMessage];
}
```

This works but has a secondary limitation: because the tool executes outside the SDK's normal stream, `output-available` state is never streamed back to the client for the previous message's tool part. Tool-specific rendering that depends on `output-available` (e.g. a "View created resource" button) only appears on page reload, not during the live session.

## Impact

Any application using `ToolLoopAgent` + `createAgentUIStream` + `needsApproval: true` with the Anthropic provider will encounter this error. The Core API workaround is non-trivial and creates secondary UX limitations.

## Notes

- The fix would be to implement the same `tool-approval-response` interception in the UI API path that exists in the Core API â€” intercept before the Anthropic provider, execute the tool, produce a `tool_result`
- Related issue: #10980
